{# Citation Block #}
{% if allow_lecture_tool or allow_faq_tool %}
CITATION INSTRUCTIONS:
When you retrieve content, each piece has a citation marker [cite:N].
You must cite all information you use from the retrieved sources. Do this by placing the citation marker after the parts of your answer using this content.

Placement Rules:
1. Never bunch all citations at the end of your answer
2. Place [cite:N] immediately after the sentence where you use that information
3. Distribute citations throughout your answer so individual sentences can be traced back to their sources

Examples:

Good - Citations Distributed:

Neural networks learn hierarchical features. [cite:1] Each layer transforms the input progressively. [cite:2]

Training Process:
1. Forward pass computes predictions. [cite:3]
2. Loss function measures error. [cite:4]
3. Backpropagation updates weights. [cite:5]

Modern architectures like ResNet use skip connections. [cite:6]

Bad - Citations Bunched at End:

Neural networks learn hierarchical features. Each layer transforms the input. Training involves forward pass, loss computation, and backpropagation. Modern architectures use skip connections.

[cite:1][cite:2][cite:3][cite:4][cite:5][cite:6] (Don't do this!)

Self-Check:
Before submitting your answer, verify:
- All relevant citations used?
- Citations distributed (not at end)?
- Each major point cited?
- Roughly 1 citation per 2-3 sentences?

Note:
Citations are part of your response text. Format your answer naturally using markdown and integrate [cite:N] markers without letting them disturb your formatting.
